<FIRST>u i AM-Argentina 3rdLead-Writethru a0729 07-09 0613</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Argentina, 3rd Lead-Writethru, a0729,0628</SECOND>
<HEAD>Menem Warns of `Surgery Without Anesthesia' to Break Ruinous Inflation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Eds: LEADS with 2 grafs to restore reference to inflation nearing
1 million percent a year; pickup 3rd graf pvs, `We have...' ^By ED McCULLOUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The new government Sunday
announced economic austerity measures that included a 53 percent
devaluation of the currency and massive utility rate increases in an
all-out effort to halt soaring inflation.
   Earlier Sunday, President Carlos Menem said Argentines must brace
for ``a very tough period'' as the government tries to halt
inflation approaching 1 million percent a year.
   ``We have to conduct major surgery without anesthesia,'' Menem
said as he arrived at Government House the morning after he was
sworn in. ``If not, Argentina has no future.''
   In a televised speech, Economy Minister Miguel Roig said that
beginning Monday the austral will sell for 655 per $1. He also
announced that natural gas rates will rise by 650 percent for
industrial users and 200 percent for homeowners.
   Natural gas is the principal source of energy for home heating in
Argentina.
   State-set rates for electricity, public transportation and other
public services will also increase substantially, Roig said in his
20-minute address. But he did not specify amounts or say when they
would take effect.
   Public Works Minister Roberto Dromi said Saturday that gasoline
prices would increase by 500 percent.
   To help Argentines cope with the increases, the government will
roll back the price of bread and other basic foods and set price
guidelines, Roig said. In addition, most workers next week will get
a special one-time payment equivalent to about $13.
   Businesses raised the price of bread and milk by more than 150
percent on Thursday and Friday in anticipation of government price
controls. Roig did not say how long the government price guidelines
on a variety of supermarket items would be in effect.
   Argentines stocked up at supermarkets when they received monthly
salaries at the end of June, and car owners lined up at gas stations
all weekend to top off their tanks.
   Roig said the government utility rates were ``absurdly low,'' and
that new rates would be ``very stiff.''
   Menem, who attended a Mass Sunday morning at the National
Cathedral and presided over a military parade, said Argentina will
have to ``endure a very tough period in order to emerge from this
crisis.''
   The inflation and the worst recession in Argentina's 173-year
history have severely hurt real wages in this South American nation
of 31 million. Low monetary reserves and a $60 billion foreign debt
leave Menem little room for easy solutions.
   The 12-month cost-of-living increase based on June's inflation
rate of 114.5 percent amounts to a staggering 948,597 percent.
   In his inauguration speech Saturday, Menem called for national
unity. He has gone out of his way since he was elected May 14 to
placate the military, smooth relations with the Roman Catholic
Church, and coordinate plans with labor unions, business groups and
rival political parties.
   It remains to be seen, however, how Argentines who have tightened
belts for several months will react to the measures, and whether
Menem will carry them out in the face of public resistance.
   Labor unions staged general strikes against former President Raul
Alfonsin when he tried austerity measures last year. The measures
triggered looting and rioting in several cities.
   The Central Bank is virtually without foreign reserves, except
for an estimated $1 billion in gold, and tax revenue has shrunk.
   Menem will find it hard to borrow from abroad, as Alfonsin did,
because the country is about $4.5 billion behind in interest
payments on the foreign debt.
</TEXT>
