<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Israel-Films     07-09 0176</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Israel-Films,0181</SECOND>
<HEAD>Palestinian, Israeli Films Awarded Festival's First Prize</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Jewish Film Festival gave first prize to the
first Israeli movie on the Palestinian uprising, and its best short
film award went to one directed by a Palestinian refugee, a jury
member said Sunday.
   An international jury awarded the $35,000 first prize to Isaac
Zepel Yeshuron's ``Green Fields,'' produced by David Tur, said jury
member and film critic Yehuda Stav.
   The movie portrays three generations of an Israeli family caught
in the violence of the 19-month-old uprising. Yeshuron, a leading
Israeli director, condemns his characters who accept violence as the
only means of dealing with the revolt.
   ``The Shelter,'' by Palestinian director Rashid Mashrawi, which
describes a day in the life of two Palestinian laborers in Tel Aviv,
was awarded the $10,000 prize for best short film. Mashrawi is from
the Shati refugee camp in the occupied Gaza Strip.
   The 10-day festival that ended Saturday featured more than 130
films from 40 countries, but competition is only among movies made
in Israel.
</TEXT>
