<FILEID>AP-NR-07-09-89 1124EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-India     07-09 0216</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-India,0223</SECOND>
<HEAD>Explosions Rock Northern Town After Buddhist and Moslem Clashes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two explosions rocked a town in northern
Jammu-Kashmir state Sunday, two days after clashes between Buddhists
and Moslems injured at least 25 people, news reports said.
   No one was killed or injured in the pre-dawn blasts in Leh,
according to United News of India and Press Trust of India news
agencies.
   ``The explosions occurred at deserted places during the night,''
PTI quoted Leh police chief G.J. Pandit as saying. Leh, a city of
100,000 people, is about 450 miles north of New Delhi.
   Authorities on Friday imposed an indefinite curfew on the city
after clashes between Buddhists and Moslems. Authorities said the
brawls were sparked by an argument between two youths.
   Several shops were set on fire and taxi drivers were dragged from
their vehicles and beaten, the news agencies said.
   The army was deployed to help restore order after police using
tear gas and batons failed to stop the fighting, the agencies said.
   About 90 million Indians, or 11 percent of the country's 880
million people, are Moslem. Jammu-Kashmir is the only state where
Moslems are in a majority. But in Leh, more than 90 percent of the
people are Buddhist. Only about 6 percent are Moslem.
</TEXT>
