<FIRST>r a AM-PolishDefectors     07-09 0736</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Polish Defectors,0761</SECOND>
<HEAD>Polish Sailors Who Jumped Ship Making Good in America</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SONNI EFRON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Six months after he defected to America by jumping
off a Polish ship, 42-year-old Wieslaw Albinski is doing just fine
in America, thanks. He's even got a new job at a computer company.
   ``In my wildest dreams I never anticipated having this kind of
job,'' said Albinski, whose English is coming along but who spoke
with the help of an interpreter. ``I had heard that there were
opportunities here but I had no idea how much.''
   Albinski was one of 48 sailors who fled from three different
Polish vessels in Boston Harbor over several days in January. All
said they were members of the then-banned Solidarity union.
   Albinski and the 47 others have applied for but not yet received
asylum in a political climate that is changing almost daily.
President George Bush left Sunday for a trip to Hungary and Poland.
It will include a two-day stop in Warsaw where he was to address a
newly elected Parliament, nearly half of whose members belong to
Solidarity _ an outlaw just six short months ago.
   Poland and Hungary are ``nations on the threshold of a new era,
nations where the spirit of freedom is strong,'' Bush said Sunday
before leaving from Andrews Air Force Base.
   But Albinski says he likes it here.
   ``There is absolutely no question that I would defect again,'' he
said during an interview last week at the Polish-American Club, as
he sat smoking Marlboros, wearing blue jeans, Reeboks and a T-shirt.
   He said he loves his new job testing computer modules at Teradyne
Inc. in Boston. But like the other sailors, he worries about his
immigration status, and whether his wife and two children in Poland
will be permitted to join him.
   The 48 have almost all been interviewed by officials with the
Immigration and Naturalization Service, but have yet to hear whether
they'll be granted asylum, said Cathryn MacInnes, the city adviser
on immigrant rights who handled the Poles' applications.
   Many of them have found jobs in the fishing industry in New
Bedford and Maine, while others are working at hotels and factories
in Greater Boston, said Jack Kowalski, the mayor's liaison to the
Polish-American community.
   Kowalski said the new arrivals got help from the community and a
local church and had no trouble finding jobs.
   ``They went off to work right away. They refused any type of
government assistance,'' Kowalski said.
   At least five of the Polish sailors are working as machinists at
Varian Associates, a vacuum products company in Lexington, making up
to $9 an hour, production manager Gerry Grenon said.
   ``They have a terrific work ethic, the old-fashioned work
ethic,'' said Grenon. ``The one problem is the language problem but
we've provided them some English-as-a-second-language training and
they're coming along.''
   Albinski was a radio operator aboard the Kantar, which pulled
into Boston Harbor just a few days after Polish sailors had jumped
another ship. Nervous about the potential for more betrayals, the
Kantar's captain was ordered not to dock but to pump fuel aboard
from another ship.
   Albinski and the others defected by jumping aboard the refueling
ship.
   As the sailors prepared to leave, the captain stood in front of
them and warned them of the ramifications, Albinski explained
through Kowalski.
   ``As I looked beyond him and saw the skyline of the city (I was)
thinking about what my future would be,'' he said.
   He jumped.
   Albinski said his American co-workers are sympathetic and
helpful, but cannot conceive of how difficult life is in Poland.
Most surprising, he said, is the absence of paranoia in the
workplace.
   ``I come and go as I please ...,'' he said. ``I can speak freely
to my co-workers. I can speak freely to you.''
   And in America, Albinski can let another secret off his chest: He
took the shipboard job only for the money.
   ``I'm not a seaman,'' he said. ``And I'm really not partial to
the sea.''
   But the merchant seamen's fate depends on whether U.S. officials
believe they are freedom-seekers or mainly just interested in better
economic opportunity.
   Timothy Whelan, deputy director of the Immigration and
Naturalization Service in Boston, said at the time of the defections
that officials would consider Poland's political climate, as well as
the lengths the sailors had to go to to leave their homeland.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
