<FIRST>r i AM-Cambodia     07-09 0561</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cambodia,0585</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nations Look Ahead to Peace in Cambodia Despite Major Barriers</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER ENG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANDAR SERI BEGAWAN, Brunei (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For the first time in almost
11 years, Southeast Asian countries and major Western allies are
seriously thinking about a world with Cambodia at peace.
   Though major barriers remain, last week's meeting of 12 foreign
ministers here underlined that virtually all the major outside
players are determined to bring about peace. They showed their
commitment to finding a settlement despite differences among warring
factions in Cambodia.
   They pinned high hopes on talks among the Cambodians starting
July 24 in Paris and on an international peace conference starting
in Paris on July 30.
   In Brunei, Foreign Minister Wong Kan Seng of Singapore said the
Cambodian conflict, which has preoccupied the region, was winding
down.
   ``We have already begun to look beyond Cambodia'' to economic
issues, he said after the conference ended Saturday.
   To examine new directions, Foreign Minister Siddhi Savetsila of
Thailand proposed a summit of the group, the Association of
Southeast Asian Nations, for next year.
   ``The important thing is that there has been a strong show of
consensus of ASEAN and its dialogue partners on the need for a
comprehensive settlement'' in Cambodia, said a senior U.S. State
Department official who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   The dialogue partners, or allies, included the United States,
Japan, and the 12-nation European Community.
   Nations at the Brunei conference said the pullout of Vietnam's
troops from Cambodia must be internationally supervised, the
Cambodian factions must share power in a provisional government
leading to elections, and an international body must also guarantee
the peace. Vietnam has pledged to withdraw all 60,000 to 70,000
troops by Sept. 30.
   Regional leaders are trying to avoid what they call ``an
Afghanistan-type settlement.''
   The Soviet Army pulled its last soldiers from that country in
February, but the Soviet-armed government is still fighting the
U.S.-backed guerrillas.
   Vying for power in Cambodia are the Vietnam-installed government
of Prime Minister Hun Sen and the guerrilla coalition led by Prince
Norodom Sihanouk, which includes the communist Khmer Rouge.
   The danger of prolonged civil war after a Vietnamese withdrawal
is very real. Hun Sen refuses to allow the Khmer Rouge in even a
provisional government. The Khmer Rouge, with up to 40,000 fighters,
reportedly has stocked arms for a major assault after Vietnamese
troops leave.
   The Khmer Rouge killed hundreds of thousands of people when it
ruled Cambodia from 1975 until Vietnam's 1978 invasion ousted it
from power.
   On Wednesday, Sihanouk again refused Hun Sen's calls to make a
separate peace without the Khmer Rouge.
   Hun Sen's side ``is very uncompromising, so there is no reason
for us to be compromising,'' the prince said at his home in Beijing.
   Still, outsiders feel guarded optimism because of the momentum of
diplomatic initiatives over the past two years. Many of these were
undertaken by Vietnamese reformers intent on rebuilding their own
country's economy and ending its international isolation.
   China, which arms the rebels, has also grown more conciliatory on
the issue in recent years, especially in toning down its backing for
the Khmer Rouge.
   The Soviet Union, which is Vietnam's major ally, has told
Washington it supports a major U.N. role in Cambodia, even though
Vietnam opposes it, according to Secretary of State James A. Baker
III.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
