<FIRST>u i AM-SoccerDisaster 1stLd-Writethru   07-09 0713</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soccer Disaster, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0636,0727</SECOND>
<HEAD>Seven Years Late, Soviet Newspaper Discloses World's Worst Soccer
Tragedy</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: SUBS 4th graf, `A front-page...' to correct typo and add that
article also appeared Sunday. Pickup 5th graf, ``According to...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police trying to cram thousands of soccer fans into
a section of Lenin Stadium in 1982 created a ``human mincer'' that
killed as many as 340 people, a newspaper said in disclosing details
of the world's worst soccer disaster.
   Sovietsky Sport, the official newspaper of the government's
Sports Committee, accused authorities of covering up the disaster
and said it was disclosing the tragedy now ``so as not to forget
people who loved sports until the grave.''
   The Oct. 20, 1982 incident had been reported before, but a death
toll and other details were never released in the Soviet Union.
   A front-page investigative story in Sovietsky Sport on Saturday
said parents believed there were as many as 340 deaths at Lenin
Stadium in Moscow's Luzhniki section. The newspaper repeated that
figure Sunday in another article about the incident.
   ``According to our information _ and no other information has
been provided to the public _ a human mincer at Luzhniki on that day
pulverized 340 lives. In the twinkling of an eye, interior troops
and police cordoned off the stadium, and also quickly surrounded the
tragedy,'' the newspaper said.
   The account said that because only 10,000 tickets had been sold
to the match between Moscow Spartak and Haarlem of the Netherlands
in the 100,000-seat stadium, management decided to cram all the fans
into one section.
   Police ringed the section, and all but one staircase was locked
``to save trouble to the police, cleaners,'' the newspaper reported.
   Police pushed fans toward the exit a few minutes before the end
of the game to prevent a jam at the nearby subway station, it said.
But when the final _ and only _ goal was scored, some fans tried to
return and collided with outgoing fans on stairs that had become
covered with ice in the 14-degree weather.
   ``It was something terrible,'' Volodya Andreyev, who survived the
accident, told the newspaper. ``We couldn't move from where we were
standing, and the crowd was pushing from above and below. It was no
longer possible to control the people who had gone crazy.''
   Sovietsky Sport said the parents of fans who failed to return
home after the match received no information from police and had to
search hospital morgues themselves. The bodies were not released for
burial for 13 days, the newspaper reported.
   Five days after the disaster, The Associated Press quoted
semi-official Soviet sources as saying more than 20 people died and
dozens were injured in a collision of fans on a ramp. A Soviet
newspaper reported casualties at the time, but did not specify
whether people were killed or injured and did not give a number.
   Sovietsky Sport reported on April 18 _ three days after 95 soccer
fans were killed in a crush at Hillsborough Stadium in Sheffield,
England _ that dozens of people were trampled to death in the 1982
Moscow incident.
   The biggest loss of life previously reported at a soccer match
was on May 24, 1964, when rioting left nearly 300 dead in Lima,
Peru, in a game between Argentina and Peru.
   The worst single-incident sports disaster in modern history
occurred when an estimated 604 people were killed after stands at
the Hong Kong Jockey Club racecourse collapsed and caught fire in
February 1918.
   Sovietsky Sports said a minor stadium official was blamed for the
1982 tragedy and sentenced to 18 months of ``corrective work,'' but
mostly the victims were blamed for alleged unruly behavior.
   Ever since the disaster, no soccer matches have been held in
Lenin Stadium at the end of October because authorities are afraid
survivors will place flowers on the field as a sign of protest.
   Readers suggested a committee be set up to investigate the
tragedy and that a meeting be held at the site Oct. 20 to
commemorate the tragedy, the newspaper said Sunday.
   The account was the latest disclosure by a Soviet media that has
seized upon President Mikhail S. Gorbachev's policy of glasnost, or
openness, to report long hushed-up Soviet disasters.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
