<SECOND>AM-Swiss Unrest,0214</SECOND>
<HEAD>Housing Protest in Zurich Turns Violent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ZURICH, Switzerland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police used tear gas and rubber
bullets to disperse 150 people who erected barricades and smashed
windows in a protest over housing shortages in Zurich, authorities
said Sunday.
   The protest Saturday night caused $100,000 in damage, injured
three officers and led to the arrests of 19 people, police said.
   A police statement said officers used tear gas and rubber bullets
around midnight after demonstrators began smashing the shop windows
in downtown Zurich and erecting barricades of garbage cans in the
streets.
   The Swiss Journalists Union charged that police attacked
journalists to prevent them from covering the violence. The union
demanded an investigation.
   Associated Press photographer Klaus Rosza said he was covering
the disturbances when police chased him into a restaurant. ``They
threw tables to the ground and three of them beat me,'' he said.
Rosza, who was treated for head and arm injuries, said a fourth
policeman sprayed tear gas in his face.
   A police spokesman denied that authorities attacked the
journalist.
   Demonstrations demanding a solution to Zurich's acute housing
shortage, especially of reasonably priced apartments, led to riots
in March that police described as the most serious disturbances
since the start of the decade.
