<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dan Quayle was back home again in Indiana
on Sunday, and he said he was not about to change a tradition of
personally taking his daughter to summer camp just because he's the
vice president of the United States.
   The vice president arrived at the Columbus airport shortly before
9 a.m., landing away from the terminal and staying away from
reporters. He left in a black limousine seven minutes later,
planning to visit relatives before taking his 10-year-old daughter,
Corrinne, to summer camp in nearby Brown County.
   The visit was described by Secret Service as strictly private.
   At Franklin, he spent about half-hour visiting his grandmother at
a nursing home. As he left, he told a group of reporters waiting
outside: ``It's good to be back home again. Things in Washington are
going well.''
   He added, ``I've always taken my daughter to camp ... I'm not
going to change that just because I'm in Washington.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Albert Gore III, the 6-year-old son of U.S.
Sen. Albert Gore Jr., is out of the hospital after an operation to
examine nerve damage from an accident in April.
   ``The senator reports that Albert's spirits are good and the
prognosis is good,'' Marla Romash, a spokeswoman for the Tennessee
Democrat, said Saturday from his office in Washington.
   The boy was seriously injured when he was hit by a car April 3 in
Baltimore after he let go of his father's hand and ran into the
street.
   He entered Ochsner Foundation Hospital here Wednesday for an
operation to examine what doctors called a stretch injury to a
network of nerves in his right shoulder. The injury limits Albert's
ability to move his forearm, said hospital spokesman Reggie Moody.
   Gore's Washington office said surgeons removed scar tissue but
decided that the injured nerve had a better chance of growing back
and restoring movement to the arm than a grafted nerve would have.
The boy left the hospital Saturday with his parents.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Rev. Billy Graham said Sunday he often receives
death threats but pays no attention to them.
   ``I have no bodyguards and I don't have anybody protecting me,''
the 70-year-old American evangelist told television interviewer
David Frost at the conclusion of his three-week British crusade.
   ``We get them quite often and I pay absolutely no attention to
them. They're just put aside. I feel like I'm clothed in the armor
of God and I'll go on as long as God wants me to and if he wants me
killed, I'm happy to be killed.''
   British news reports said Graham defied death threats from
fundamentalist Protestants on Saturday night by appearing with
Northern Ireland singer Dana, a Roman Catholic, at London's Wembley
Stadium.
   Graham said he was not aware of those specific threats.
   Political and sectarian violence between Catholics and
Protestants in Northern Ireland has left more then 2,700 people dead
over the last 20 years.
   He also told Frost he received a letter from Nelson Mandela, the
African National Congress Leader jailed in South Africa, saying he
had turned to Christianity.
   ``He invited me to come and see him,'' Graham said. ``He said
that about three or four years ago he had received Christ into his
heart, he was reading and studying the Bible.''
   Graham did not say when he received the letter.
   Graham said 1.25 million people attended his 13 rallies in
Britain, including 85,000 who braved heavy rains Saturday at Wembley
Stadium.
