<FILEID>AP-NR-07-09-89 1441EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-SouthAfrica     07-09 0576</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-South Africa,0596</SECOND>
<HEAD>Activists Pleased at Mandela-Botha Meeting; Family Skeptical</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURINDA KEYS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Anti-apartheid leaders said
Sunday they were encouraged by a meeting between between President
P.W. Botha jailed black leader Nelson Mandela, but a spokesman for
Mandela's wife was skeptical.
   ``At long last a head of state was heeding the calls of those who
are interested in negotiations,'' Anglican Archbishop Desmond Tutu
told a Cape Town news conference.
   ``In some ways you could say it is the outgoing president meeting
someone who is going to succeed him in Tuynhuys,'' he said,
referring to the official residence where Botha talked with Mandela
for 45 minutes Wednesday.
   Tutu said there was ``more to be gained than to be lost'' in
meeting with Botha, who ``is after all still the state president. He
still does call the shots.''
   Botha is to step down after elections in September.
   Mandela, imprisoned since 1962, is serving a life term for
sabotage and plotting to overthrow the white-dominated government.
He is regarded as the leader of the outlawed African National
Congress, and many black South Africans want him to be their
president. Other black leaders refuse to negotiate with the
government until he is freed.
   The ANC has not made any comment on the meeting.
   Colin Eglin, former leader of the now-defunct anti-apartheid
Progressive Federal Party said the meeting appeared in part an
attempt to get white South Africans used to the idea that the ANC
leader will be released from prison soon.
   ``Mandela's public image is being changed from that of the enemy
to someone who visits the president at his home,'' Eglin said in an
interview.
   But at a news conference at Winnie Mandela's home, the Rev. Frank
Chikane, secretary-general of the South African Council of Churches,
said the government ``is taking advantage of the position of Mr.
Mandela, trying to give the impression to the world that they are
negotiating with him when they are the only ones who have access to
him.
   ``If a leader is put in a situation where he is not able to
consult the people he represents, the people are not able to
indicate they have any hope in what has happened,'' he said.
   Chikane said his comments reflected the views of community
leaders who met at Mrs. Mandela's home, but he did not name any of
them.
   Mrs. Mandela let Chikane speak for her, answering only one
question, about whether she thought the meeting meant Mandela would
be freed soon.
   ``We haven't the slightest idea. It is impossible to analyze the
present indications,'' she said.
   Leaders of major anti-apartheid groups ostracized Mrs. Mandela in
February because of what they called a ``reign of terror'' by her
bodyguards in Soweto, the black township outside Johannesburg. Since
then she has made few appearances.
   Zulu leader Mangosuthu Buthelezi, who is preparing for
negotiations with exiled ANC President Oliver Tambo to end fighting
between black political groups in Natal province, said ``all men of
goodwill will applaud the meeting between these two sons of South
Africa.''
   Zulu youths who oppose Buthelezi and support ANC policies cheered
when the Botha-Mandela meeting was mentioned during a Durban rally
Sunday that drew 6,000 people.
   The rally was called by the Congress of South African Trade
Unions, involved in the peace negotiations with Buthelezi's Inkatha
organization to stop violence that has taken some 2,000 lives in
Natal in the past three years.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
