<FIRST>r w AM-Abortion-States     07-09 0263</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Abortion-States,250</SECOND>
<HEAD>Florida's Anti-Abortion Governor Says Compromise Possible</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Florida Gov. Bob Martinez, who favors calling a
special session of the state's legislature to enact new restrictions
on abortions, said Sunday he expects ``very aggressive'' lobbying by
both sides but hopes there will be no resort to violent tactics.
   ``I believe there is a compromise that can be reached between the
rights of the unborn and the rights of women,'' said Martinez,
himself an abortion opponent.
   The Republican governor, appearing on ABC's ``This Week With
David Brinkley'' program said areas of possible compromise include
permitting abortions in cases of rape, incest or where the mother's
health is threatened.
   Although he has not yet made a final decision, Martinez said he
prefers calling a special session of the legislature in October.
   Also interviewed on the program was Vermont's Democratic Gov.
Madeleine Kunin, who criticized the Supreme Court's decision last
week upholding a Missouri statute restricting abortions.
   ``What the Supreme Court has really done is created a different
standard in each state,'' she said. ``It's created turmoil where
there was an uneasy truce. And it's wrenched open a very, very raw
wound. The kind of emotional and antagonistic debate that has
erupted is going to be very, very tough.''
   Gov. Kunin called the Missouri law's ban on using taxpayer
dollars to fund abortions ``a dangerous restriction because so many
women are dependent on public funds.''
   `` And when you take away public funds,'' she said, ``you really
take away their choice as to whether and when they want to have a
child.''
</TEXT>
