<FIRST>u i AM-Lebanon 1stLd-Writethru   07-09 0635</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0648,0655</SECOND>
<HEAD>Beach Crowd Trapped on Sand as Militias Battle; Three Fighters Killed</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Leads with 11 grafs to UPDATE with beaches evacuated. Pickup
10th pvs, `In Beirut...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RODEINA KENAAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of sunbathers were trapped on
south Beirut beaches for hours Sunday as rival Shiite Moslem
militiamen battled with machine guns, mortars and rocket-propelled
grenades in nearby neighborhoods, police said.
   Syrian troops in charge of security in Beirut's Moslem sector
arranged a one-hour ``mercy cease-fire'' at sundown and evacuated
the trapped beach goers, said a police spokesman.
   ``It was like a horror movie... Flocks of people ran in every
direction as grenades and gunfire burst in the air,'' said Massara
Kahwaji, a homemaker who joined an evacuation convoy as she returned
to west Beirut from a weekend in south Lebanon.
   Also Sunday, Syrian gunners in north Lebanon fired sporadic
barrages at the Christian enclave's coast to prevent a ship
suspected of carrying arms from docking.
   The Syrian guns opened up again in late afternoon, shelling the
Christian residential districts of Baabda, Yarzi and Hazmiyeh
southeast of Beirut. Police said two people were wounded.
   By police count, 403 people have been killed and 1,576 wounded
since the March outbreak of the Christian-Syrian confrontation.
   Three people were killed and nine were wounded in the militia
violence in south Beirut, said the police official who spoke on
condition of anonymity.
   That brought the overall toll to 11 killed and 37 wounded in the
current confrontation, which erupted nine days ago between the
pro-Syrian mainstream Amal militia and the Iranian-backed,
fundamentalist Hezbollah, or Party of God.
   The militias are vying for power over Lebanon's 1 million Shiite
Moslems.
   The fighting blocked all escape routes from south Beirut's Ouzai
and Jnah districts and stranded thousands of people on the sand
throughout the day.
   Syrian armored personnel carriers took many evacuees to coastal
villages south of the capital, while others were escorted back to
west Beirut as sniper fire crackled overhead.
   In Beirut, Syrian and Christian troops traded sniper fire along
Beirut's dividing Green Line, forcing a one-hour closure of the only
open gateway between the Moslem and Christian sectors of the city.
   The hostilities were evidence that Arab League trouble-shooter
Lakhdar Ibrahimi had failed to make headway in his four days of
talks with Christian and Moslem leaders in Beirut.
   Ibrahimi wound up two days of talks with the army leader, Gen.
Michel Aoun, and other Christian leaders in east Beirut on Saturday.
On Sunday, he met with Moslem Parliament members in west Beirut.
   One parliamentarian, requesting anonymity, said Ibrahimi was
trying to arrange a meeting of the Lebanese Parliament outside
Lebanon to draw up political reforms that would give Moslems an
equal share of power with the Christians.
   The Christians have dominated the government, army, Parliament
and judiciary since Lebanon gained independence from France in 1943,
when Christians were thought to be the majority.
   According to experts, Moslems are now the majority of Lebanon's 4
million people. They have been fighting in the 14-year-old civil war
for political equality.
   Parliament has been unable to meet in Beirut since September,
when President Amin Gemayel's term expired with no successor elected.
   The source said Ibrahimi contends that once political reforms are
drafted, chances will improve for holding a Parliament session in
Beirut to elect a new president, who would form a national coalition
Cabinet to carry out the reforms.
   Minutes before stepping down, Gemayel named Aoun, a Maronite
Catholic like himself, prime minister of a military caretaker
Cabinet.
   Moslems rejected Aoun's appointment and pledged allegiance to
Syrian-backed, acting Prime Minister Salim Hoss, a Sunni Moslem who
governed under Gemayel.
   The split splintered the army and police along sectarian lines
and eventually led to the outbreak of the current Christian-Syrian
confrontation.
</TEXT>
