<FIRST>r a AM-HouseSaved     07-09 0231</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-House Saved,0237</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Saved From Falling Into Sinkhole</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RIDLEY PARK, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It took 1,900 tons of dirt and rock and
10 hours of labor into the night, but workers triumphed over a
20-foot sinkhole threatening to devour John and Betty Priest's
house, although they did lose the front lawn. ``It's good being
back,'' Priest said Saturday. ``There's nothing like it.''
   The couple had to be evacuated last week when flood waters caused
Ridley Park Lake to overflow and opened the sinkhole.
   Borough engineer James Kelly, who ordered the evacuation, thought
any more rain might cause the hole to widen and possibly destroy the
home. But then he and Pennsylvania Department of Transportation
officials came up with the plan to fill the hole.
   Workers using several trucks Friday, worked almost non-stop
hauling fill materials of dirt and rocks to the Priest home. The
stuff had been excavated at a nearby highway construction site and
was unneeded, officials said.
   Volunteers from nearby fire companies kept roads open for the
trucks and provided lighting that allowed the filling to continue
after dark.
   ``I never saw anyone work like those guys did,'' Priest said.
   ``When I read in the papers about people who were flooded out and
lost everything, we were lucky,'' he said. ``We didn't lose anything
but the front lawn. There wasn't a drop of water in the house.''
</TEXT>
