<FILEID>AP-NR-07-09-89 1549EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-KoopSuccessor     07-09 0709</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Koop Successor,690</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lower-Profile, Less-Independent Surgeon General Sought</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As C. Everett Koop closes out a seven-year,
high-profile stint as the nation's surgeon general, officials in the
Bush administration are wrangling over whether they want his
successor to enjoy the same visibility.
   Though he possessed very little statutory power, Koop used the
office as a bully pulpit to hammer at the hazards of smoking, raise
the nation's awareness of AIDS and become, as he puts it, the
``health conscience'' of America.
   Although technically his office is within the Department of
Health and Human Services, Koop was an independent surgeon general _
at times a little too independent to suit some conservatives in the
Reagan White House.
   ``I'm not clear that office will ever again hold the stature it
did under Koop,'' said Jean McGuire, director of the AIDS Action
Council.
   It's not clear whether the Bush administration wants it to.
   While the White House is collecting names of possible nominees
for the job, some in the administration want its profile lowered.
   According to sources who spoke on the condition of anonymity,
thought has even been given to simply adding surgeon general to Dr.
James Mason's title as assistant HHS secretary for health, a move
that is not without precedent.
   Chase Untermeyer, personnel director for President Bush, declined
to speak directly to the varied opinions circulating. But, he said,
``We're proceeding on the assumption that it will be separate from
Dr. Mason.''
   About 15 names are on a list of people who have indicated they
are interested in the job or have been recommended by others,
Untermeyer said, refusing to identify any of them.
   ``The names have been coming in on their own since it was made
public (in early May) that Koop would be leaving,'' he said.
   Burton Lee, the president's personal physician, said he is
``pushing for a woman'' to get the job and has recommended the names
of several he believes are qualified. He declined to identify any of
them, but said none is a well-known public figure.
   ``It's turned out to be quite a political job,'' Lee said, and
will probably become even more so with the Supreme Court's ruling
last week giving states more authority to limit access to abortions.
   ``No matter who you get, they're going to be the subject of a lot
of criticism,'' he said.
   One name that has surfaced is Dr. James H. ``Red'' Duke, a noted
trauma surgeon at the University of Texas Medical School in Houston
and host of PBS' ``Bodywatch.''
   Supporters of the 60-year-old ``cowboy'' doctor say he's got the
same kind of charisma and communications skills that worked so
successfully to make Koop an American folk hero.
   A name mentioned by conservative groups is Dr. Robert Redfield,
chief of retroviral research at Walter Reed Army Institute of
Research.
   But Gary Bauer, a former Reagan White House aide who now heads
the Family Research Council, said conservative groups ``are only now
beginning to focus on (the vacancy) and realize it's an important
post.''
   AIDS activists, who heap kudos on Koop for taking the lead on
AIDS and speaking openly about condoms and sex education to prevent
its spread, are also watching to see who his successor will be.
   They are heartened that Lee _ who served on the President
Reagan's AIDS commission _ has Bush's ear as the president's
personal physician.
   ``A strong person with moral persuasions on this issue could be a
real problem,'' the AIDS Action Council's McGuire said. ``Koop
helped break down the moral impediments around AIDS .... My biggest
fear would be someone who would build them up again.''
   As for Koop, the 72-year-old pediatrician will step down this
week and begin writing his memoirs and looking for media
opportunities to continue preaching his health messages.
   In a recent session with reporters, Koop said his activism and
independence strengthened the office of surgeon general and give his
successor ``a better opportunity of accomplishing things.''
   Asked how he would advise his successor, Koop said recently:
``Don't try to copy me or anybody else. ... Do what you can do and
be who you are to the very best of your ability. That's exactly what
I did.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
