<FIRST>r i AM-Honecker     07-09 0198</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Honecker,0204</SECOND>
<HEAD>East Germany Silent on Honecker's Health</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 24 hours after reporting that Communist
Party chief Erich Honecker was suffering from a gallbladder ailment,
East Germany's state-run media on Sunday remained silent on the
76-year-old leader's condition.
   Honecker was forced to return home early from a Warsaw Pact
summit in Bucharest, Romania, on Saturday. The official news agency
ADN said then he was suffering from an ``acute gallbladder
ailment.'' It did not say if Honecker had been hospitalized and gave
no other details.
   It said, however, that Honecker congratulated Premier Willi Stoph
on his 75th birthday, but that the greeting was conveyed by Egon
Krenz, a senior member of the Communist Party's Politburo and deputy
head of state.
   Krenz, 52, often has been mentioned as the top candidate to
succeed Honecker as party chief.
   Honecker became party leader in 1971 and assumed the additional
post of head of state in 1976.
   During recent public appearances, Honecker seemed to be in robust
health and alert.
   But West German newspapers reported in recent months that he
appeared to lose concentration and showed speech problems during
various meetings with West German officials visiting East Germany.
</TEXT>
