<FIRST>r i AM-Sudan     07-09 0295</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sudan,0306</SECOND>
<HEAD>Military Ruler Announces Formation of New Cabinet</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DALIA BALIGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KHARTOUM, Sudan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sudan's new military leader, Lt. Gen. Omar
Hassan Ahmed el-Bashir, Sunday announced formation of a Cabinet that
will try to end the nation's six-year civil war and revive its
faltering economy.
   The 21-member Cabinet, in which el-Bashir doubles as prime
minister and minister of defense, was announced over state
television by Brig. Mohamed Sulaiman, a member of the ruling junta
who acts as government spokesman.
   The country has a $13 billion foreign debt and spends $1 million
daily fighting southern rebels led by turncoat army Col. John
Garang. They want greater regional autonomy.
   The cabinet is to be sworn in on Monday. But Western diplomatic
sources have said they do not expect the junta, a 15-man military
council headed by el-Bashir, to yield decision-making power to the
Cabinet.
   The junta was formed after el-Bashir ousted Prime Minister Sadek
el-Mahdi in a coup on June 30.
   The Cabinet includes three members of the military council, four
southerners and two former officials who worked under former
President Gaafar Nimeiri but broke with him shortly before his
ouster in 1985.
   El-Bashir's deputy in the military council, Brig. El-Zobair
Mohamed Saleh, was appointed deputy premier. Two other junta members
appointed were Brig. Faisal Abu-Saleh, as police minister, and Lt.
Col. El-Tayeb Ibrahim, as minister of presidential affairs.
   Foreign Minister Aly Sahloul, Finance Minister Sayed Ali Zaki and
Minister for Health and Social Welfare Shaker el-Serag served as
underscretaries in their respective ministries before el-Bashir's
coup.
   The southern Cabinet appointees are Abdallah Deng Niyal, minister
of guidance; Nataly Yelker Ambo, minister of local governments;
Edward Ador, minister of relief; and the Rev. George Kenga, minister
of labor and social insurance.
</TEXT>
