<FIRST>r a AM-ChappaquiddickLawsuit     07-09 0385</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Chappaquiddick Lawsuit,0393</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Investigator Sues Author of Book on Chappaquiddick</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former state police detective who investigated
Sen. Edward M. Kennedy's 1969 accident at Chappaquiddick is suing
the author of a book on the incident, claiming the author never paid
for his information.
   Bernard J. Flynn, the police detective lieutenant, claims that
author Leo Damore promised him $50,000 for his cooperation when
Damore was writing ``Senatorial Privilege,'' an account of the
accident in which the senator's 28-year-old passenger, Mary Jo
Kopechne, was killed.
   ``This is a contract that is oral in nature,'' Flynn's attorney,
Gary A. Nickerson, told the Boston Sunday Herald. ``However, there
are some written memorandums that reflect the existence of an oral
contract.''
   The fatal Chappaquiddick accident, which also helped to kill
Kennedy's hopes of being president, occurred 20 years ago this
month, on July 19, 1969.
   Flynn told Damore that he met secretly on at least two occasions
with Kennedy's brother-in-law, Stephen Smith, and lawyer, Herbert J.
Miller, to pass along information about the district attorney's
probe into the accident.
   Damore said he paid Flynn $1,000 to cover expenses but said he
never promised the investigator any money.
   ``I told him `you can't be paid for this information,''' Damore
said. ```You'll hurt yourself and you'll hurt the credibility of the
information,' I said to him, `as far as money is concerned, forget
it.' There was no contract here, none.''
   Damore has filed to dismiss the lawsuit, but said that if it goes
to trial he might be forced to subpoena Kennedy, Smith and Miller.
``That alone is worth $50,000,'' said the author.
   The book was published in 1988 by Regnery Gateway, a conservative
publishing house based in Washington, after it had been rejected by
a number of New York publishers. Damore, of Old Saybrook, Conn., is
a former Cape Cod resident who has written several books, including
a flattering account of John F. Kennedy's years on the Cape.
   One of the Chappaquiddick book's most controversial revelations
was an allegation that Kennedy wanted to tell police that Kopechne
had been driving alone on the night of the crash. That account was
based on interviews with Kennedy associate Joseph Gargan, who went
with the senator and another friend, Paul Markham, to try and rescue
Kopechne after the accident.
</TEXT>
