<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Moldavia     07-09 0351</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Moldavia,0363</SECOND>
<HEAD>Moldavians Mass in Huge Rally</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of ethnic Moldavians and opponents from
non-native groups gathered Sunday in a tense demonstration, Soviet
TV reported.
   ``Today in Kishinev, there was a flaming tinder but there was no
explosion due to the balanced steps taken by law enforcement
bodies,'' a correspondent reported from the Moldavian capital in the
western Soviet Union.
   It did not say what steps authorities took to calm the situation.
   Members of groups demanding more rights for ethnic Moldavians
carried tri-color nationalist flags and banners and shouted slogans
such as ``Moldavia to Moldavians'' and ``Get out, Occupiers,'' the
correspondent said on the evening news program ``Vremya.''
   One huge red banner visible amid the thousands of people on
Kishinev's main square read, ``We aren't Guests, we are Home!'' That
appeared to be a slogan of non-ethnic Moldavians who are members of
a largely Russian group, Interfront, and feel threatened by the
nationalists' demands.
   Soviet TV said Kishinev officials had authorized Sunday's rally
but wanted it to be a forum for dialogue between opposing groups.
Instead, the demonstrators heckled a Moldavian representative to the
national parliament, the Congress of People's Deputies, according to
the television report.
   Ethnic Moldavians have been agitating for months with strikes and
demonstrations to have their native language restored to its
original form. They also have complained about crime and
environmental problems.
   Moldavia has long retained close ties with Romania, its neighbor
to the west, despite repeated attempts by Moscow to link it more
closely with Russia.
   The region of 4.2 million people has passed from Turkish to
Russian to Romanian and back to Soviet control over the past century.
   Moldavian and Romanian are the same spoken language, but the late
dictator Josef Stalin imposed the Cyrillic alphabet on the
Moldavians after Soviet troops occupied the region during World War
II.
   Moldavian Communist Party chief Semyon Grossu in February
condemned nationalist activists for going too far but endorsed some
of the language demands. Draft legislation that would gradually
reinstate the Latin script still used in neighboring Romania has
been published for public discussion.
</TEXT>
