<FILEID>AP-NR-07-09-89 1907EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-DelawareSpill-Tanker     07-09 0373</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Delaware Spill-Tanker,0385</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tanker That Spilled Oil into Delaware River Leaves for Repairs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MARCUS HOOK, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Uruguayan supertanker that spilled more
than 300,000 gallons of oil into the Delaware River last month left
Sunday for repairs in the West Indies.
   The cleanup of the June 24 spill is about 80 percent complete,
``but we'll be at it for several more weeks,'' said Coast Guard
spokesman Jim Weakley.
   The tanker Presidente Rivera left this oil refinery city just
southwest of Philadelphia and steamed down the Delaware Bay,
reaching the Atlantic Ocean shortly after noon, Weakley said.
   The 749-foot-long ship's destination is Curacao, a West Indian
island about 170 nautical miles northwest of Caracas, Venezuela,
Weakley said.
   A Coast Guard tug, patrol boat and helicopter escorted the vessel
12 miles down the river from Marcus Hook to the Delaware Memorial
Bridge to watch for leaks, the spokesman said. No contamination was
spotted.
   Two commercial tugboats and a skimmer vessel used to clean up the
spill also accompanied the tanker to the bridge.
   The helicopter remained over the Presidente Rivera until it
reached the mouth of the bay, and made periodic overflights after,
Weakley said. A Coast Guard representative was aboard the ship until
it reached Lewes, Del., at the mouth.
   The tanker had been scheduled to leave Saturday, but was delayed
because an overboard discharge monitor had to be replaced, Weakley
said. The monitor measures the amount of oil lost when a ship pumps
out water taken on as ballast.
   The ship passed a final inspection by the American Bureau of
Shipping before leaving.
   The tanker's bottom has been temporarily patched and oil has been
cleaned off its hull, Weakley said.
   The tanker ran aground June 24 off Claymont, Del., near the
Delaware-Pennsylvania line, ripping open its bottom and spilling
300,000 gallons of thick, tarry industrial heating oil.
   The cleanup of the Delaware River has recovered about 400,000
gallons of oil and debris, Weakley said.
   The Presidente Rivera is expected to reach Jacksonville, Fla., in
five days, and is scheduled to go into drydock in Curacao on July
26, he said.
   The investigation into the accident is continuing, and it may be
several months before a cause is determined, Weakley said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
