<FILEID>AP-NR-07-09-89 1826EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Bush 3rdLd-Writethru a0679 07-09 1307</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0679,1,200</SECOND>
<HEAD>EDS: Inserts grafs 3-5, ``He did not xxx with background on economic
austerity and 24th graf, ``Despite the xxx with color; trims in bottom
third to tighten; SHOULD STAND for AMs</HEAD>
<HEAD>Bush to Poles: ``The World is Inspired by What is Happening Here''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush, on a delicate and historic
mission to accelerate renaissance in Poland and Hungary, told the
Polish people Sunday the world is inspired by their struggle but
cautioned it ``will require further sacrifices.''
   ``History _ which has so often conspired with geography to deny
the Polish people their freedom _ now offers up a new and brighter
future for Poland,'' Bush said upon his late-night arrival in Warsaw
after a nine-hour flight from Washington.
   He did not elaborate on his prediction of sacrifice ahead for the
Polish people, but administration officials have made clear any U.S.
aid will be tied to economic austerity measures by the Poles
themselves.
   The Poles declined to approve a severe economic austerity program
two years ago that would have raised food prices and put other
pressures on their already lean economic existence.
   Officials said at the time the program would send prices for such
consumer services as rent and heating up as much as 200 percent and
that the price for basic food items such as milk, bread and meat
might double.
   Bush was greeted by Polish leader Gen. Wojciech Jaruzelski and
Prime Minister Mieczyslaw F. Rakowski as he came down the ramp of
his airplane.
   Also present was Andrzej Wielowieyski, deputy speaker of Poland's
new freely elected Senate and an adviser to Solidarity leader Lech
Walesa. It was the first time a Solidarity representative has been
included at an official Polish state welcome.
   After inspecting a military honor guard and shaking hands with
dignitaries invited to the airport ceremony, Bush and Jaruzelski
strode to a speaker's platform for their brief remarks.
   Before leaving his own capital, Bush had made clear he is
sensitive to the two Warsaw Pact nations' need to transform
themselves without antagonizing the Soviet Union, which borders both.
   ``It is not our role to dictate to them what they should be doing
or the refinements of the system,'' he said at a departure ceremony.
   In Poland, Bush said ``winds of change surely have touched the
land here where so much has happened since my last visit'' two years
ago as vice president.
   ``Poland has started a long and ascending path of democratic
change,'' he said. ``This climb is accelerating but will not always
be easy and will require further sacrifices. But if followed, it
will lead to a renaissance for this remarkable nation.
   ``These are great days for Poland,'' Bush continued. ``Solidarity
is again legal. The beginnings of a free press now exist. A new
parliament is in place. The Polish senate has been restored through
free and fair elections. Poland is making its own history. And
America, and the world, is watching.
   ``The world is inspired by what is happening here,'' he said.
``Here in the heart of Europe, the American people have a fervent
wish. ... That Europe be whole and free.''
   Tactfully, Bush promoted Jaruzelski, the country's communist
leader, who was at the airport when the U.S. president's plane
touched down.
   ``The government of Poland and you, Mr. Chairman, have shown
vision and courage in taking the path of the round-table accords,''
the president said. He made no mention of Jaruzelski's role in
trying to break Solidarity and in imposing martial law in December
1981.
   The Polish leader greeted Bush as an ``outstanding politician and
statesman, the leader of the great American people with which the
Poles are linked by lively ties of friendship based on long
tradition.''
   Jaruzelski said, ``Warsaw residents who have come in such great
numbers to see you and greet you this summer evening are giving an
expression of this.''
   Despite the late hour, thousands of people scattered in groups
along Bush's 4.5 mile motorcade route cheered and waved as he rode
past. Some of them waved huge American flags as Bush pulled out of
the airport, a large crowd waved and many people shouted
``Solidarity.''
   In his departure statement in Washington, Bush had said Poland
and Hungary were ``on the threshold of a new era'' and that Europe,
``a continent cruelly divided for more than four decades, now dreams
of being whole and free.''
   In a conciliatory gesture toward Moscow that signalled his
determination to end the Cold War era, the president said his task
was ``to see that we mend old divisions, that we fulfill the
decades-old dream, and that the new Europe emerges _ secure,
prosperous, peaceful and free.''
   Bush's 10-day trip also will take him to a summit meeting in
Paris with the leaders of Britain, Canada, France, Italy, Japan and
West Germany and include a side trip to the Netherlands _ the first
official visit by a U.S. president to America's oldest diplomatic
partner.
   But the emphasis will be on Bush's visits to Poland and Hungary,
the two Soviet bloc countries with the most pronounced trend toward
a Western-style economy and a democratic political system.
   The symbolism of it all is immense: No U.S. president has visited
a Warsaw Pact nation since Jimmy Carter went to Warsaw in 1977 and
never has a U.S. president been to Hungary.
   Bush's goal is to wean Poland and Hungary from Moscow's orbit and
toward a more independent foreign policy. But the president is being
careful not to couch his mission in competitive terms _ nor to
exhort Poles and Hungarians into reckless actions that could
backfire.
   In a television interview aired as the Bush party was flying
across the Atlantic, White House Chief of Staff John Sununu said
Bush's offer of economic aid to Poland will be a ``measured
response.''
   ``The one thing that might create ... a wedge rather than a
continued movement of reciprocal progress would be to put such a
large package in there that the Poles would perceive that we are
trying to replace the Soviet Union's support with support from the
West,'' he said on CBS-TV's ``Face the Nation.''
   ``That's not our intention,'' Sununu said. ``We are not trying to
replace. What we are trying to do is augment.''
   As for challenging Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev, who
barnstormed in West Germany last month and has just completed a
visit to France, Bush disavowed any intention of being provocative.
   ``I think if we went there with hot rhetoric and our goal was to
complicate things for Mr. Gorbachev, yes, there would be a danger,''
Bush said just before Air Force One took off from Andrews Air Force
Base and headed toward a sun just climbing above the eastern horizon.
   ``But I think I know enough about it ... and others upon who I'm
relying know enough about it ... and know that's not going to
happen,'' he told reporters.
   At the same time, Bush vowed: ``I'm not going to back off my
principles because it might offend Mr. Gorbachev. I'm not going to
try to put him in a box by throwing strains on the Warsaw Pact. I
will give my aspirations for a Europe whole and free. What we want
to do is encourage them.''
   Jaruzelski, in an interview on CNN's ``Newsmaker Sunday''
program, said Bush's visit was taking place ``at a very important
moment'' in history and ``that is why I see President Bush's visit
as an element that would favor the positive processes which are
already taking place and which are bringing East and West closer
together.''
   Recalling the talks that were held when Bush visited Warsaw as
vice president two years ago, Jaruzelski said he recognized then
that ``Poland's matters are very close to him (Bush) and understood
by him.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
