<FIRST>r i AM-Afghanistan     07-09 0317</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Afghanistan,0331</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Ammunition Warehouse Explodes in Kabul</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DILIP GANGULY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A major government arms warehouse
exploded and burst into flames near the city's airport Sunday
destroying a large quantity of ammunition and weaponry, witnesses
said.
   The explosion in eastern Kabul occurred close to midnight Sunday
and shook buildings up to five miles away. It was not immediately
known what caused the blast but the city has been the target of
rocket attacks by Moslem guerrillas in the past week.
   The fire burned for more than two hours throwing glowing shrapnel
into the night sky. It grew into a towering column of smoke.
   The extent of damage, and the type and quantity of weaponry
destroyed, was not immediately known.
   Reporters were unable to visit the spot because of a 10 p.m.-to-4
a.m. curfew imposed by the government.
   Foreign Ministry Spokesman Mohammad Nabi Amani said Sunday that
as many as 50 rockets hit the capital during the week, killing at
least 15 people.
   The insurgents began fighting after a communist coup in April
1978. Soviet forces intervened in December 1979 to back the
government. Their withdrawal was mandated under a U.S.-mediated
accord, and the Red Army completed the pullout on Feb. 15.
   The guerrillas attacked Jalalabad, Afghanistan's fifth-largest
city, on March 6 in their first major assault after the Soviet
withdrawal. The city would provide the insurgents with a seat for
the government they formed in Pakistan, where they have their
headquarters.
   On Saturday, Foreign Ministry spokesman Mohammad Nabi Amani said
government troops were in complete control of Jalalabad and
surrounding hills, giving them a strategic advantage over the rebels.
   He also said government forces backed by a tank regiment had
destroyed guerrilla bases and killed 81 insurgents as they advanced
two miles to come within 32 miles of the Pakistan border.
   The government reports could not be independently confirmed.
</TEXT>
