<FIRST>u a AM-HousewaresShow     07-09 0450</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Housewares Show,0467</SECOND>
<HEAD>Housewares Show: Lightning Bolt Hair and Microwave Tie-Dye</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL A. DRISCOLL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lightning-bolt hair, microwave tie-dying and palm
trees that dance to music were among the brave new possibilities
offered at a national trade show Sunday.
   Thousands of gadgets and appliances from more than 600 producers
were on display at the National Housewares Manufacturers Association
show.
   The three-day show, which ends Tuesday, brings producers and
buyers together and allows for a midyear assessment of the
housewares industry as the Christmas buying season approaches.
   ``Personal care is a billion-dollar business, kitchen electric is
multibillion,'' said Frank Lindsey, vice president for marketing of
Conair Corp. of Stamford, Conn. Both are among the multitude of
products considered housewares.
   One trend appears to be putting patterns in hair, and the
appliance industry is trying to stay one jump ahead of demand.
   Enter Impressions, a waffle iron-like device made by Conair that
embosses designs like jagged lightning bolts in hair. Its suggested
retail price is $29.95.
   Want to tie-dye a T-shirt, but short of time? There's Micro-Dye,
a $3.49 kit by Dylon Corp. of Youngsville, N.C., that allows one to
tie-dye in a microwave oven in four minutes.
   ``It's a 60s to the 90s look,'' said Scott Krueger of Dylon.
   The Zojirushi Home Bakery is ``the next stop'' in automatic
bread-making machines, said show spokeswoman Susan Fleishman. In
addition to fresh bread, the $325 appliance makes jam, cake and
frosting.
   ``It's very much for the sophisticated cook,'' said Ms. Fleishman.
   For sore muscles or tired feet, there's the personal massager,
another item on the move. Massagers were a $30 million industry last
year, and producers are expected to double that by the end of 1989.
   ``Massagers have been more popular in Japan and Europe, and it's
time the U.S. woke up,'' said Richard Stern of Associated Mills Inc.
of Chicago, which sells under the brand name of Pollenex.
   ``We've come out with 16 new products this year,'' Stern said,
``and the twist massager is going to be a tremendous product.'' The
42-inch rope-type device goes for a suggested price of $29.95.
   For those who want to cool their throats, there's SodaMaster, put
out by SodaMaster Co. of America of Decatur, Ga.
   ``Add the fun of fizz to any drink,'' the company says.
   SodaMaster sells for $150, and adds carbonation to juices, water,
wine or any cold drink.
   For that one more item to make life complete, there's the Dancing
Palmtree by Gemmy Industries Corp. of Irving, Texas, which goes for
$15 wholesale.
   The artificial palm tree about a foot tall sports sunglasses and
sways back and forth when exposed to music, almost like it's dancing.
</TEXT>
