<HEAD>Charge Woman with Killing Kids in Case Police Gave Up On in '82</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after 11th, ``We wanted...' to include that Mrs.
Johnson and her new husband do not have children; picks up 12th graf pvs,
`Jennyann reportedly.'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARC RICE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOCUST GROVE, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The investigation of the deaths of four
children seemed to have hit a dead end seven years ago, until a
newspaper reporter's questions led an officer to read through the
file and reopen the case.
   Now Martha Ann Johnson, 34, who originally blamed her children's
deaths on bad luck, has been accused of killing them in separate
incidents from 1977 to 1982. Formal charges were filed last week in
three of the deaths, and police say she has confessed to the fourth
death.
   Police say Mrs. Johnson smothered the children, at least twice
after fights with her then-husband, but at the time of the deaths
they did not have solid evidence to back their suspicions and bring
charges.
   Authorities have said the case originally fell through the cracks
when officials failed to communicate with one another. Police,
social and medical agencies in Fulton and Clayton counties were
involved.
   ``The `cracks' did result in part from the number of agencies and
crossing jurisdictional lines,'' Clayton District Attorney Robert E.
Keller said. ``But you've got to acknowledge also there were flaws
in what was done.''
   A few hours before her arrest last Monday, police say, Mrs.
Johnson confessed to investigators from neighboring Clayton County
to killing 2-year-old James William Taylor in 1977 and 11-year-old
Jennyann Wright in 1982.
   She was indicted Thursday in Clayton County on charges of
murdering Jennyann, and also 3-month-old Tibitha Janeel Bowen in
1980 and 3-year-old Earl Wayne Bowen in 1981. James died in Fulton
County and that case will be handled there, said Fulton County
District Attorney Lewis Slaton.
   The case was placed on ``no lead'' status in 1982, leaving it
dormant, because there ``just wasn't enough to go with,'' said
Clayton County police Maj. Jerry Robinson. The deaths of Tibitha and
James, for example, were originally attributed by medical examiners
to sudden infant death syndrome.
   The investigation was reopened in December after an inquiry about
the case by a reporter from The Atlanta Journal-Constitution who was
doing a story on how government agencies handle deaths of juveniles,
Robinson said. County police Director Ronnie Clackum reviewed the
case file and decided to reopen the investigation, he said.
   ``What we did when we reopened the case, we went back to square
one,'' Robinson said. He would not comment on specific evidence, but
said the new investigation included interviews with people who were
not included in the first investigation.
   ``We wanted to make sure everything was in line before we
interviewed Mrs. Johnson,'' Robinson said. Since the time of the
last death, she had remarried and moved to Locust Grove, a town of
about 2,000 some 45 miles south of Atlanta.
   Mrs. Johnson and her new husband do not have children of their
own.
   Jennyann reportedly asked for help from her natural father and a
social worker, but was returned to her mother after being placed for
a time with another relative. She was found Feb. 21, 1982, face down
on her mother's bed, dead from what medical examiners at the time
called ``unexplained asphyxia.''
   ``You'd have to say the system failed in this,'' Keller said.
   Police have refused to say how Mrs. Johnson allegedly killed the
children, though the Atlanta newspaper reported that in at least two
cases she is suspected of having smothered them with her body.
   ``It seems that every time that she would get into an argument
with her husband and he would leave, something would happen to one
of the children,'' Robinson said.
   During the first investigation, Robinson said, there were ``real
strong feelings'' that a crime had been committed. And pathologists'
reports at the time made note of the previous deaths, he said.
   But he noted that to arrest someone, there must be probable cause
that a crime was committed. After the children died, he said, police
``went to the prosecutors that were handling this case and presented
what they had to them. It was just a general feeling that there just
wasn't enough to go with.''
</TEXT>
