<HEAD>Northwest Airlines Jetliner Lands After Smoke Noticed</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: REVISES number of passengers in lead, SUBS last graf, `The smoke...'
to further pinpoint source of smoke and attribute to airline official.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Northwest Airlines jetliner with 222
people aboard made an emergency landing minutes after takeoff Sunday
because of smoke in the cockpit.
   The Minneapolis-bound DC-10 returned to San Francisco
International Airport at 12:55 p.m. after dumping fuel over San
Francisco Bay, air traffic control manager Michael Corbett said at
the Air Traffic Control Center in Fremont.
   Passengers got off the plane upon its return to the terminal for
repairs.
   ``It turned out to be a minor smoke problem ... so it's no big
deal,'' Corbett said.
   The smoke was attributed to oil spilling on the engine, an
airport spokesman said. The smoke then was drawn through the
aircraft's air conditioning system, said Kevin Whalen, director of
corporate communications for Northwest in Eagan, Minn.
