<FIRST>r w AM-Poland-BushArrival     07-09 0511</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland-Bush Arrival,520</SECOND>
<HEAD>Star-Spangled Banner and Goose-Stepping Troops ^With AM-Bush</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President George Bush's arrival at Warsaw
Military Airport on a sweltering summer night included a
goose-stepping military honor guard, a Solidarity representative and
a bit of Polish speaking by the president.
   ``Czolem,'' Bush shouted in a firm voice to the high-booted
troops who formed the honor guard. The traditional military greeting
usually is translated as ``hail.''
   ``Hail, Mr. President,'' the troops shouted back in Polish.
   The nation was able to watch Bush's long-anticipated arrival live
on television, from the time Air Force One taxied onto the runway at
10:01 p.m. until his motorcade left for a government guest house on
the edge of a Warsaw park.
   Poland is in the midst of a rare summer heat wave, with
temperatures in the 90s. Through the open windows in city streets,
the broadcast of Bush arriving could be heard coming from almost
every apartment.
   Polish Communist leader Gen. Wojciech Jaruzelski, looking
excited, greeted the smiling president as he came down the steps of
the U.S. jet, accompanied by his wife, Barbara.
   Also present were young boy and girl scouts, who presented Bush a
bouquet of red and white roses, the colors that make up the Polish
flag. ``This kid speaks beautiful English,'' Bush could be heard
saying about one child.
   In a sign of the historic changes that have take place in Poland
in recent weeks, one of the first dignitaries in the line to greet
Bush was Andrzej Wielowieyski, deputy speaker of Poland's new freely
elected Senate and a senior adviser to Solidarity leader Lech Walesa.
   It was the first time a Solidarity representative has been on
hand for an official state welcome ceremony. As he waited,
Wielowieyski mingled easily with members of the government.
   In his brief welcoming remarks, Jaruzelski, wearing a civilian
suit, told Bush, ``You are coming to a land in which a process of
fundamental changes is underway.''
   Bush replied, ``There is a great deal of work to be done. And we
will work together to gain new ground, to expand our common
ground...Long live Poland.''
   Then the army and air force troops, carrying sabres and rifles
with shiny bayonets, goose-stepped away as Bush and Jaruzelski
looked on.
   Crowds lined the road leading from the airport to watch Bush's
speeding motorcade pass.
   ``He's a terrific guy. We're very happy he came, but he went by
too fast,'' joked a middle-age female office worker after the column
of dozens of cars sped past.
   ``For Poland, this is a very important thing, a visit from the
president of the United States,'' said a professor watching near his
home in the city's Ochota district. ``The emotional support is the
most important thing ... We also hope there will be some monetary
deal'' from the visit.
   The professor's neighbor, an English teacher, said, ``Everyone
expects...Some arrangements to help us out of this economic crisis.''
   She added that as an educator, she looks forward to more student
exchanges with the United States.
</TEXT>
