<FIRST>r w AM-Abortion     07-09 0501</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Abortion,520</SECOND>
<UNK>Abortion Foes Predict New Election Fights</UNK>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court decision giving states new
authority to restrict abortions means a new round of fights in the
states about the contentious issue, two women on opposite sides of
the dispute agreed Sunday.
   ``It's the voters who are going to hold the candidates to a new
level of accountability and they're going to lose their jobs,'' said
Kate Michelman, executive director of the National Abortion Rights
Action League.
   Susan Smith, associate legislative director for the National
Right to Life Committee, disagreed. ``We've proven that the pro-life
margin is enough to help elect pro-life representatives.''
   But Ms. Michelman disputed that, saying, ``no, no, no, no, no.''
   The debate occurred on ABC-TV's ``This Week with David Brinkley.''
   The disagreement by the women mirrored comments a week ago in the
wake of the 5-4 Supreme Court decision which said the states could
have new authority to restrict abortion. Representatives of both
sides said the fight would now turn to state legislatures.
   Ms. Smith said, ``we're going to do what we've been doing for the
past 16 years(since the 1973 Supreme Court decision legalizing
abortions).
   ``We have a very strong grassroots organization in place, which
has been very active in helping to pass protective legislation, the
kind of legislation that's finally been upheld by the Supreme Court
after years of striking down even minimal restrictions.''
   ``There are a lot of people out there who for many years now have
felt that they have been unable to do anything about this issue,''
she said. ``What the Supreme Court did was to return aspects of this
issue back to the democratic processes and the people.''
   But Ms. Michelman said, ``you know the lives and health of women
should not depend on the accident of their residency any more than
the right of the freedom of the press should depend on where a
newspaper is published.''
   ``We may have lost faith in five justices of the court, but we
have not lost faith in the American public,'' she said.
   She said one target will be Florida Gov. Bob Martinez, who said
he is willing to call the Florida legislature into special session
to write new restrictions on abortion.
   Martinez said he expects intensive lobbying from both sides.
   ``I suspect that it will be very aggressive, no question about
it, from both sides,'' he said. ``I would hope that we each enjoy
the freedom of speech, but do it without harm to anyone, without
damaging public or private property, that we communicate our
thoughts and be as aggressive as you like. I know it's an aggressive
kind of issue.''
   Gov. Madeleine Kunin of Vermont said ``I hope we can develop
another way that we don't have to just respond emotionally, that we
can realize the world has changed, and women have become used to the
idea that our present day other choices of freedom include the idea
of choosing when, whether they want to have children.''
</TEXT>
