<FIRST>r a AM-GasPrices     07-09 0234</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Gas Prices,0240</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gas Prices Down Despite Summer Demand</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gasoline prices continued an uncharacteristic
summer decline caused by increased oil and gasoline supplies, an
analyst said Sunday.
   The nation's average retail price for a gallon of gasoline was
$1.16.76 on July 7, a decrease of 1.67 cents since early June, said
Trilby Lundberg, publisher of the biweekly Lundberg Survey of 12,000
gas stations.
   The price has dropped because refiners, terminal operators and
importers had increased supplies to meet new federal clean-air
regulations, Lundberg said.
   ``The drop reflects efforts on the part of the oil industry to
step up their gasoline production and imports of gasoline during May
and June in order to avoid any supply tightness or shortage,''
Lundberg said.
   Lundberg said that higher demand by summer drivers and policy
changes in other oil producing nations could still push prices
higher later this year.
   Gasoline reached its peak average price of $1.18.43 per gallon on
May 19, a sharp rise at the time from the average price of 98.04
cents in early January, the survey found.
   At the self-service pump July 7, regular unleaded gasoline cost
an average of $1.06.78 per gallon, while premium cost $1.22.52 per
gallon and regular leaded was $1.06.12 per gallon.
   For full-service gasoline, the average cost for unleaded was
$1.32.11 per gallon, premium cost $1.44.03 per gallon and regular
leaded was $1.30.5 per gallon.
</TEXT>
