<FIRST>r a AM-BoyFound 1stLd-Writethru a0698 07-09 0421</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Boy Found, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0698,0428</SECOND>
<HEAD>Missing Child, 3, Walks Out of Woods After Two Days</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: RECASTS lead to DELETE erroneous reference to family owning
the dogs, SUBS 2nd graf to explain; INSERTS 2 grafs after 6th, `He was...'
to UPDATE with quotes from father; picks up 7th graf pvs, `Lt. Neil...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARILYNN WHEELER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 3-year-old boy who disappeared last week
emerged from dense woods with three dogs Sunday, walked up to search
crews and asked for a cookie.
   Joseph Edwin Leffler was hungry and had wet feet but was
otherwise fine, authorities said. He had gone into the foothills of
the Cascade Range on Friday on an imaginary fishing trip with a
neighbor's dogs, two adult Australian shepherd dogs and a small
white puppy.
   ``I knew that if any 3-year-old could survive, Joe could do it,''
said his his tearful mother, Judy Leffler, 38.
   Joseph probably survived by sleeping with the dogs, said Robert
L. Norton, an emergency room physician at the hospital.
   The boy, dressed in a short-sleve shirt, pants and high-top
sneakers, left his house about 1 p.m. Friday. He carried a 3-foot
length of plastic pipe to use as a pretend fishing pole.
   He was reported missing after he failed to return from Fall
Creek, just 200 feet away from the family home.
   The boy's father, Daniel Leffler, said he didn't lose hope that
his son would be found safe because the two had spent a lot of time
together in the woods. He said he had a lot of confidence in the
dogs, which belonged to Virgil Williams, a family friend with whom
the Lefflers had been staying for about six weeks.
   ``Virgil told us, `Don't worry, my dogs will sleep with him and
keep him warm,'' said Leffler. The boy later said he'd slept with
the dogs both nights and that they'd helped him find his way out of
the woods.
   Lt. Neil James of the Clackamas County sheriff's office estimated
300 people were involved in the search Sunday morning. The effort
included several teams of tracking dogs and a helicopter from the
Air Force Reserve's 304th Air Rescue and Recovery Squadron in
Portland.
   The boy came into view about a three-fourths of a mile from where
he disappeared. The dogs were trotting alongside.
   A helicopter took Joseph to Oregon Health Sciences University
Hospital, where doctors said he would stay overnight for observation.
   The youngster gave a ``thumbs up'' sign to onlookers at the
hospital.
</TEXT>
