<FIRST>r a AM-UrbanDolphin     07-09 0246</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Urban Dolphin,0253</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dolphin Found Dead in Hudson</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A dolphin that spent more than a week in city
waters, resisting efforts to herd it back to sea, was found dead
Sunday in the Hudson River nearly 50 miles north of here.
   The bottlenose dolphin was found floating off the town of
Garrison on the east side of the river, said marine biologist Samuel
Sadove of the Okeanos Ocean Research Foundation, which rescues
stranded sea mammals.
   The sea mammal was alive Saturday, Sadove said in a telephone
interview.
   An autopsy was to be performed on the gray, 5-foot-long animal at
an Okeanos laboratory in Hampton Bays on Long Island, where the
organization is based.
   Sadove declined to speculate on what caused the animal's death,
but said it was not unexpected. He said last week that its condition
had noticeably deteriorated. The dolphin's skin was peeling due to
the lack of salt in the Hudson.
   The dolphin, of the same species as the dolphin that appeared in
the television show ``Flipper,'' was first spotted June 20 in the
East River off Manhattan.
   It stayed in the river for 11 days, attracting a steady stream of
curious onlookers.
   The dolphin resisted efforts by biologists who tried to herd it
back into the Atlantic Ocean by banging on pipes in the water.
   Two weeks ago, it headed north up the Hudson. Scientists had
planned to capture the dolphin Tuesday and take it to the sea.
</TEXT>
