<FIRST>r a AM-Newspage-Wimbledon     07-09 0207</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Newspage-Wimbledon,0213</SECOND>
<HEAD>A German Sweep of Wimbledon, Becker and Graf Win</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WIMBLEDON, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Boris Becker beat Stefan Edberg in
straight sets Sunday, to win his third Wimbledon title in five
years, and Steffie Graf won her second straight title in the women's
final, overcoming Martina Navratilova.
   Becker avenged his loss to Edberg last year, winning the
championship rematch 6-0, 7-6, 6-4, the most one-sided final since
John McEnroe allowed Jimmy Connors only four games in 1984.
   The 21-year old West German regained the title he won in 1985 and
1986.
   Graf, for the second year in a row, halted eight-time champion
Navratilova's bid for a record ninth Wimbledon singles title 6-2,
6-7, 6-1. It was her sixth victory in the last seven Grand Slams.
   Graf, 20, who lost to teen-age Arantxa Sanchez in the French Open
final last month, sat in her sideline chair on Centre Court after
the victory, bowed her head and sobbed.
   ``I wanted it so badly that I put a little more pressure on
myself than usual,'' Graf said. ``It's an overwhelming feeling.''
   The women's final was postponed from Saturday because of rain and
darkness, putting both finals on the same day for only the 10th time
in Wimbledon history.
</TEXT>
