<FIRST>r a BC-Theater     07-09 0578</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Theater,0589</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Twelfth Night,' All-Star Shakespeare, Opens in Central Park</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: No PMs planned.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL KUCHWARA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Drama Critic</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The widely publicized all-star revival of
``Twelfth Night'' by the New York Shakespeare Festival is bawdy,
boisterous, even boorish _ an idiosyncratic, often low comedy
jokefest that sacrifices love, not to mention Shakespeare, for
laughs.
   The reason? There are a lot of stars on stage at the Delacorte
Theater in Central Park, where ``Twelfth Night'' opened Sunday, and
director Harold Guskin has encouraged them to revel in their own
eccentricities, no matter what it does to the play.
   Because of that directive, the production belongs to the
strongest performers, in this case, Gregory Hines, a consummate song
and dance man. Hines, dressed to look like a mummer in a
Philadelphia New Year's Day parade, plays Feste, the fool.
   Feste dominates the evening, even making the quartet of lovers _
Viola and Orsino, Olivia and Sebastian _ seem like supporting
characters. Out the window goes much of the play's ideas about
romance, particularly concerning sexual identity and illusion as
well as its more thoughtful moments about death and reconciliation.
   Viola, dressed as a boy, still pines for Orsino who longs for
Olivia who sighs for the young man Viola pretends to be. And Viola's
long-lost twin brother Sebastian still arrives to straighten out the
mess. But they all seem secondary to the comic business at hand.
   Most of that business, fortunately, concerns Hines who has the
grace, style and personality to get away with just about anything,
even dropping his pants or dancing with surprised female members of
the audience.
   He's helped in the comic antics by John Amos, a gruff,
inarticulate Sir Toby Belch, and Fisher Stevens as the effete Sir
Andrew Aguecheek. Stevens displays a goofy charm accentuated by a
straw-blond wig that makes him look like a dissipated Breck shampoo
girl.
   Jeff Goldblum gives the production's strangest performance.
Playing Malvolio, Olivia's villainous steward and would-be suitor,
Goldblum scampers around the large stage as if he were auditioning
to replace Mikhail Baryshnikov as the cockroach in
``Metamorphosis.'' His speaking voice is even stranger. Oozing
insincerity, he affects a sing-song, stop-and-go cadence that
obliterates any sense of Shakespeare's language.
   Michelle Pfeiffer, a wan, indifferent Olivia, also tramples many
of her speeches, rushing through them before she finds herself out
of breath. There is more life _ and feel for the language _ to be
found in Charlaine Woodard as Olivia's sprightly maid Maria.
   Stephen Collins as a stuffy, even sexist Orsino and Graham Winton
as Sebastian are adequate but bland. The best member of the quartet
of lovers is Mary Elizabeth Mastrantonio. She conveys Viola's sense
of sexual confusion and desperation in great comic style, but the
actress doesn't neglect the music to be found in Shakespeare's
moonstruck poetry.
   Director Guskin has set the play at the turn of the century in a
Mediterranean country, not unlike Monaco. It allows costume designer
Jeanne Button to provide some elaborate costumes. And set designer
John Lee Beatty has conjured up a peach-colored marble gazebo that
dominates one side of the stage, with a tiny replica of Olivia's
house perched on a rocky cliff on the other side of the playing area.
   ``Twelfth Night'' ends with a wistful song by Feste, delivered by
Hines with great feeling. It releases a wide range of emotions that
are missing from the mostly one-note, relentless buffoonery that
precedes it.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
