<FIRST>r i AM-Germany-Aquino     07-09 0222</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Germany-Aquino,0229</SECOND>
<HEAD>President Aquino Criticized for Human Rights Abuse in Philippines</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Philippine President Corazon Aquino
heard strong criticism of human rights violations in her country
when she arrived in West Germany on Sunday.
   Beginning a three-nation tour to encourage a greater European
role in the development of the Philippines, Mrs. Aquino traveled to
West Berlin, where she met with Mayor Walter Momper.
   ``It would be insincere not to mention that many people in this
city are concerned over the persistent and growing violations of
human rights in the Philippines,'' Momper said at a reception for
Mrs. Aquino.
   Momper cited ``arbitrary arrests, murders and disappearances of
people, and torture.''
   He also praised Mrs. Aquino's struggle for political change by
peaceful means after 20 years of rule by ousted President Ferdinand
Marcos.
   In brief remarks to West German television reporters, Mrs. Aquino
said her government was committed to protecting human rights. She
said violations were not widespread and that most attacks on
civilians were carried out by communist insurgents, not by
government forces.
   Mrs. Aquino's talks with West German leaders begin on Monday,
when she is to meet President Richard von Weizsaecker and Foreign
Minister Hans-Dietrich Genscher. On Tuesday, she will meet with
Chancellor Helmut Kohl.
   Mrs. Aquino's weeklong tour will also take her to France and
Belgium.
</TEXT>
