<HEAD>Ortega Holds Airport Meeting With Venezuelan President</HEAD>
<UNK>Eds: CORRECTS in 5th graf that San Jose agreement was created in 1980
sted 1979; Pickup 6th graf, `Perez and...'</UNK>
<DATELINE>CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Daniel Ortega of Nicaragua
traveled to Caracas Sunday afternoon aboard a Cuban plane for a
two-hour airport meeting with President Carlos Andres Perez, sources
said.
   Two photographers and a reporter from a Caracas newspaper were
arrested by soldiers guarding the runaway at Maiquetia airport as
they tried to approach the plane. Other reporters were expelled from
the building.
   The three arrested were released about an hour later.
   Ortega landed at 6 p.m. on a Cuban-owned, Soviet-made Ilyushin
jet on his way back from the inauguration of President Carlos Menem
of Argentina. The plane departed 10 minutes after the meeting ended.
   The subject of the talks was not known. Sources who spoke on
condition of anonymity said they may have centered on the 1980 San
Jose agreement, under which Venezuela and Mexico sell oil to Central
American and Caribbean nations on easier terms. Nicaragua was
excluded from the agreement seven years ago for non-payment.
   Perez and President Carlos Salinas de Gortari of Mexico, in
Venezuela on a three-day visit, Monday were to sign an accord
extending the agreement for another year.
