<FIRST>u a AM-NebraskaFire 3rdLd-Writethru a0705 07-09 0711</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nebraska Fire, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0705,0729</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fire Burns Out of Control in Northwest Corner of State</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf with 2 grafs to CLARIFY that governor's declaration
made state funds available, UPDATE with number of Guardsmen ordered to
help battle fire; picks up 3rd graf, `The fire ...' INSERTS 1 graf after
7th graf, ```We could ...' to UPDATE with governor flying over fire, quote;
picks up 8th graf, `In addition ...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Fires Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto SCO1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KURT REPANSHEK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CRAWFORD, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A lightning-sparked fire raged out of
control Sunday along a 20-mile front in northwestern Nebraska,
threatening the community of Crawford and forcing evacuation of a
hospital, a nursing home and a park.
   Gov. Kay Orr issued an emergency declaration for the area, making
state money available, and ordered about 30 National Guardsmen to
help an estimated 150 firefighters battle the blaze.
   The blaze also threatened the site of a former Army cavalry post
where Sioux Chief Crazy Horse was killed.
   The fire burned to within 1{ miles of the city of 1,300 and
authorities feared a shift in the wind could endanger the town.
   The fire started Saturday on the west side of Fort Robinson State
Park and Park Superintendent Vince Rotherham estimated that 10,000
to 12,000 acres trees, scrub and grassland in the 22,000-acre park's
rugged canyons had burned. It also had charred part of an adjoining
wildlife refuge and private land.
   ``It looks really bad. A lot of those trees are 150 years old.
... It will take 100 years to rebuild it,'' Rotherham said.
   The blaze grew to about 20 miles long and six miles wide, had
burned 50,000 to 100,000 acres and was far from contained, said
deputy state fire marshal Jerry Larson.
   ``We could see whole lines of trees exploding,'' said Marc
Anthony, a state game and parks commissioner who flew over the fire.
A mushroom cloud of smoke could be seen from Scottsbluff about 90
miles away.
   ``It's not a pretty sight,'' said Mrs. Orr, who flew along the
perimeter of the blaze. ``There's so much, only so much that can be
done, and they're doing everything humanly possible,''
   In addition to a rugged landscape of buttes as high as 4,900 feet
and long, narrow canyons, temperatures around 90 degrees and
variable wind complicated firefighting efforts, officials said.
   ``Everything was against us,'' Rotherham said. ``It's been
extremely hot. When it hit, it just kind of exploded things. This
area is extremely rough _ they couldn't get to it.''
   About 150 firefighters from about 25 to 30 departments from
Nebraska, South Dakota and Wyoming were fighting the blaze, he said.
   About midday, the fire inside the park was within one-half mile
of historic Fort Robinson, the former cavalry post where Crazy Horse
was killed by guards in 1877, Rotherham said.
   Larson said an undetermined number of private cabins had burned
in the sparsely populated area.
   Crawford Hospital treated several people for minor injuries, said
nursing supervisor Jacqueline Skavdahl.
   Earlier, the four patients at the hospital were taken by bus to
the Chadron Community Hospital because of the smoke and closeness of
the flames, said Kathy Wigington, Chadron director of nursing
services. And about 25 residents of the Ponderosa Villa nursing home
were taken to a dormitory at Chadron State College.
   ``The elderly people are at higher risk. They don't breathe as
well,'' said Kathy Owen, director of nursing services at the nursing
home.
   More than 600 visitors were evacuated from the campgrounds, lodge
and cabins at Fort Robinson State Park because of the shifting wind
and smoke, although authorities said there was no immediate danger
to the tourist facilities, said Rotherham.
   ``It was extremely smoky, just so you could just about breathe,''
Rotherham said.
   State Sen. Sandy Scofield, who lives on a ranch near Chadron,
said the fire was the worst she has seen in the area.
   ``There have been three big fires out here in 15 years and right
now I think that this is probably the worst of all of them,'' she
said Sunday.
   Scofield said the rough country will hamper firefighting efforts.
   ``I don't know how they can go about fighting a fire like that,''
she said. ``It's been very dry out here.''
</TEXT>
