<HEAD>Teen-Ager Slashed When She Saves Mom From Ax-Wielding Robber</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 4th graf, `An arrest...' with 3 grafs to UPDATE with arrest
made; picks up 6th graf pvs, `Rose leaped...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 16-year-old girl charged at a robber who
was holding an ax to her mother's throat, saving her mother but
getting slashes that required 200 stitches, authorities said.
   ``He said, `If you scream again, I'll hit you even harder,' and I
just screamed louder,'' said Rose Lacy as she recovered from
Saturday's attack at her family's copy business. ``I saw blood
everywhere but I didn't know how badly I was hurt.''
   ``All I could think of was that I had to get that ax away from my
mother's neck,'' she said.
   Alvin Haynes, a 32-year-old ex-convict who has been living at a
nearby halfway house, was arrested Sunday and was being held at the
city jail, Lt. John Brunner said.
   Haynes was taken into custody after his sister called police and
said her brother was ready to turn himself in, Brunner said.
   Brunner said the assailant entered the Rose Copy shop _ named for
the girl _ about noon and asked to use the bathroom. He apparently
opened a tool box inside the store, took out an ax and held it to
the throat of Rose's 33-year-old mother, Melody Lacy.
   Rose leaped at the man's arm, but he knocked her down and struck
her twice with the 4{-inch blade. Despite the gashes across her
cheek and the back of her head, the girl jumped to her feet and
chased the robber around the store.
   The man then grabbed cash that had been placed on a counter and
ran away, police said. The amount of money taken was not disclosed.
   Mrs. Lacy said her daughter's attacker ``seemed frightened when
she got up and started chasing him with half her face falling off.''
   Rose Lacy was treated and released at San Francisco General
Hospital, where she received 200 stitches.
</TEXT>
