<FIRST>r a AM-MissingWomen     07-09 0416</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Missing Women,0432</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hearing Scheduled Monday for Suspect in Kansas Slaying, Disappearances</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY JORDEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A painter held for questioning in the slaying of a
Kansas woman and the disappearances of three others was talkative,
but isn't giving authorities anything they can make a case on, a
police chief said.
   ``He's not a dummy. He'll admit to things, but not to the point
that it implicates him,'' said Wichita, Kan., Police Chief Rick
Stone, who was in Dallas on personal business when Richard Grissom
Jr. was arrested Friday.
   Grissom, who remained jailed without bond Sunday, said he knew
the three missing women, Stone said.
   The 28-year-old house painter planned a date with Terri Maness,
25, of Wichita the night of June 7, when she was strangled and
stabbed in her townhouse, Kansas authorities said.
   Grissom was being held at Lew Sterrett Justice Center for alleged
parole violations, said Dallas County sheriff's Lt. Gary Lindsey.
Grissom has not been charged in the slaying or the disappearances.
   A hearing was scheduled for Monday to begin extradition
proceedings, Lindsey said.
   On Saturday Grissom, acting on his attorneys' advice, refused to
sign papers allowing his extradition to Kansas City, even though he
earlier agreed to cooperate with authorities.
   Members of the Overland Park, Kan., Metro Squad, who'd planned to
take the suspect back to the Kansas City suburb Saturday, returned
home empty-handed.
   ``He is going to be here for a while,'' said Lindsey. Extradition
can take 60 to 90 days.
   Officials with north Texas law enforcement agencies questioned
Grissom about unsolved slayings in their region, but he didn't
provide much information, authorities said.
   Grissom was arrested at Dallas-Fort Worth International Airport
on an anonymous tip.
   An avid bodybuilder, Grissom was convicted at age 16 of
bludgeoning a 72-year-old Lansing, Kan., woman to death with a
railroad spike.
   Jewelry, credit cards and other belongings of at least one of the
missing women were recovered from a car at the airport which was
stolen in Missouri and which Grissom allegedly drove to Texas, said
Overland Metro Squad Detective Larry Keller.
   Police want to question him about the disappearances of Lexena,
Kan., roommates Christine A. Rusch and Theresa J. Brown, both 22,
said Keller. The suburban Kansas City women were reported missing
June 26.
   Overland police began seeking Grissom June 27 in the
disappearance of 24-year-old Joan Butler, who was reported missing
June 16.
   Grissom is on parole for a burglary and theft conviction in
Kansas.
</TEXT>
