<FILEID>AP-NR-07-09-89 1519EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-NameChanges Bjt   07-09 0611</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Name Changes, Bjt,0630</SECOND>
<HEAD>Survey Shows Decline in Corporate Name Changes in First Half</HEAD>
<HEAD>Embargoed until 12:01 a.m. EDT Monday; Time set by source.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A few memorable names such as the Eastern
Airlines Air-Shuttle, The First Women's Bank and Gulf &amp; Western Inc.
disappeared from corporate record books in the first half of the
year.
   But overall, the number of U.S. companies that changed their
names fell 18 percent in the first six months of 1989 compared with
a year ago, the first such decline in four years, according to a
survey for release Monday.
   The identity consulting firm Anspach Grossman Portugal Inc.
attributed the decline to a slower pace of business merger activity
than a year earlier.
   The firm said 767 American companies changed their names in the
January through June period, down from a record 931 name changes in
the first six months of 1988. It was the first such decline since
1985.
   Despite the slower pace of merger activity, mergers and
acquisitions remained the most frequently cited reason for name
changes in the latest period, accounting for 351 changes, or 46
percent of the total.
   Corporate downsizing, spinoffs and asset sales accounted for 177
of the name changes or 23 percent of the total.
   The Air-Shuttle, for instance, was renamed the Trump Shuttle
after developer Donald Trump bought it from troubled Eastern.
   The survey said there were 139 elective name changes, or 18
percent of the total. Included among these were The Home Group
Inc.'s adoption of the name AmBase Corp., Middle South Utilities
Inc.'s change to Entergy Corp. and American Hoist &amp; Derrick Co.'s
switch to Amdura Corp.
   The remaining name changes were done to reflect corporate
restructuring or reorganization, changes to a holding company and
other assorted changes in legal status.
   Joel Portugal, a principal at Anspach Grossman Portugal, said
some companies are finding value in sticking with their names or a
shortened version of them rather than creating entirely new names.
   He said they have found an existing name ``can have real value,
like any other corporate asset.''
   He said F.W. Woolworth Co. appeared to be following that strategy
by streamlining its name to Woolworth Corp., and Eastern Gas &amp; Fuel
Associates did so by changing to Eastern Enterprises.
   Even Gulf &amp; Western, which became Paramount Communications Inc.
last month, turned to an old Hollywood name many people recognize,
Portugal said.
   New England Apple Products Co. Inc., a maker of bottled fruit
drinks, capitalized on its major brand name by changing to Veryfine
Products Inc., and Austin Rover Cars of North America became
Sterling Motor Cars.
   The number of thrifts, banks and other financial institutions
that changed their names fell to 195 in the latest six-month period,
down from 254 a year earlier, the survey stated.
   It said an increasing number of thrifts dropped the ``S&amp;L'' from
their names in favor of ``bank,'' possibly reflecting recent
concerns about the large number of thrifts that have required
federal assistance.
   One of the more unusual name changes by a bank was the decision
by The First Women's Bank to change its name to First New York Bank
for Business. The New York-based bank _ which formerly catered
almost exclusively to women customers _ said the change reflected
its belief that women no longer were discriminated against by other
banks and by a decision to expand into middle market commercial
lending.
   Overall, Anspach Grossman Portugal said, the number of
manufacturers changing their names outpaced changes by financial
institutions for the first time, 229 to 195.
   The next most frequent changes by industry were 64 in
communications, 57 in technology and 37 in retailing.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
