<FIRST>r f AM-Ford-Petersen     07-09 0446</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ford-Petersen,0462</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ford Lowers Estimate of 1989 Industry Sales</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DEARBORN, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ford Motor Co. has dropped its estimate of
the number of cars and light trucks likely to be sold this year
industrywide by up to 300,000 vehicles, further evidence of a
softening car market.
   Ford Chairman Donald Petersen on Friday lowered the company's
estimate to about 14.7 million from about 15 million cars and
trucks, an estimate the company held for months.
   Chrysler Corp. Chairman Lee Iacocca last month predicted a sales
year of 13.5 million to 14 million vehicles, with roughly two cars
being sold for every light truck. General Motors Corp. has held to
its 15 million vehicle estimate with the same breakdown between car
and truck sales.
   Petersen backed away from the car-to-truck ratio, saying he
expected truck sales this year to remain at last year's level of
about 5 million units. That means the reduction in sales volume
would come from the car market.
   ``I'm sure the June (sales) numbers were the thing that knocked
them off their pedestal, so to speak,'' said auto analyst Joseph
Phillippi of Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. in New York.
   Earlier this week, Ford reported its domestic car sales during
June were running 12.3 percent behind the pace during the same month
last year. General Motors Corp.'s June car sales were 12.4 percent
lower than last year's and Chrysler Corp.'s were down 17.5 percent.
   But sales during June of last year were exceptionally strong,
mostly because of attractive incentives.
   This June incentives also were offered, but they didn't generate
the same kind of buying interest as they did in 1988, a fact
Petersen acknowledged Friday.
   Last year was the second-best sales year in industry history,
with 15.8 million cars and light trucks driven off dealership lots.
The 16.3 million vehicles sold in 1986 made that year the best in
history.
   Although he expected lower sales volume for the industry,
Petersen said it would still be a good year.
   ``The auto industry has been coming down gradually since its peak
in 1986,'' Petersen said after receiving an award as manager of the
year from the National Management Association.
   ``We've had quite a run here,'' Phillippi said of the past five
years of vehicle sales. ``We have been due for a correction.''
   While GM and Chrysler have been losing market share during the
past year, Ford has been gaining.
   Also on Friday, Petersen said more plant closings and layoffs are
possible during the third quarter beyond the normal breaks for
summer vacation and model changeovers. However, he addedm that he
didn't think the layoffs would be significant or long-lasting.
</TEXT>
