<FIRST>u f AM-GreekBankSuit     07-09 0475</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Greek Bank Suit,0490</SECOND>
<HEAD>Greek Bank To Be Sued for $1.5 Billion By Angry Depositors</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID ROCKS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Greek bank whose U.S.-based officers are charged
with racketeering bilked depositors of hundreds of millions of
dollars, an attorney alleged Sunday.
   The depositors plan to file a class-action lawsuit Monday seeking
$1.5 billion in damages from the National Mortgage Bank of Greece
and 14 of its officers, said Constantine Kangles, lead attorney in
the lawsuit.
   The bank is the subject of a racketeering investigation by
federal authorities, who on June 21 raided branches in four states,
seizing documents and arresting the officers.
   A federal complaint filed in U.S. District Court in New York
charges the bank with illegally accepting more than $700 million in
deposits from customers in the United States and sending the money
overseas to avoid taxes.
   ``You had widows investing ... all the money they had to get the
higher interest rates'' offered by the Greek bank, Kangles said.
``There's nothing they can do. There's a deep feeling the money's
not there.''
   Bank officers told customers that interest _ as much as 18
percent a year _ would be paid in Greek drachmas and would not be
subject to U.S. taxes, Kangles said.
   He said about 300 people were party to the lawsuit and that their
ranks could swell to as many as 3,000. He said the $1.5 billion
represented treble damages based on a conservative estimate of about
$500 million in deposits.
   The National Mortgage Bank of Greece is a separate entity from
the National Bank of Greece, which also operates in the United
States. The National Bank of Greece owns about 47 percent of the
mortgage bank, federal authorities say.
   Phone numbers for the mortgage bank's Chicago-based officers were
unlisted, and calls Sunday to the two Chicago-area branches went
unanswered.
   According to court documents, the bank advertised in
Greek-language newspapers, promising that the accounts would be
secret.
   ``They put it in the newspaper,'' Kangles said. ``Almost
everybody believes what they read in the newspaper.''
   The seven branches, in Illinois, Massachusetts, New York and
Pennsylvania, were not even legally authorized to accept money from
customers in the United States, authorities say. Rather, the
branches were opened with the ostensible purpose of encouraging
investment in Greece.
   Kangles said some depositors had gone to Greece to try to get
their money back, and were told accounts were frozen.
   Some of the depositors could face criminal charges if it is shown
they willfully sought to evade taxes, Kangles said. But he said most
of the people did not report the money on their tax returns because
they believed the bank's claims of tax-free status.
   Part of the damage award the depositors are seeking would go to
pay penalties the depositors would owe the Internal Revenue Service,
Kangles said.
</TEXT>
