<FIRST>r f AM-Eastern-Strikers     07-09 0468</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eastern-Strikers,0484</SECOND>
<HEAD>Controversial Organizer Meets With Striking Eastern Workers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN GALVIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Maverick labor organizer Ray Rogers met with about
200 striking Eastern Airlines flight attendants Sunday, urging them
to broaden their battle beyond the picket lines and target the
airline's stockholders and other investors.
   ``These workers have tremendous skills that can be put to use,
whether it's canvassing neighborhoods, putting together mailings ...
or speaking to the media,'' Rogers, 45, said after the meeting at a
hotel at Logan International Airport.
   ``They've got to be mobilized, they've got to be transformed into
a powerful economic and political force that can go out and build
economic and political support,'' he said.
   With the strike in its fourth month, the Transport Workers Union
of America hired Rogers last week to try to bring the strike to a
successful end. Rogers said he and the union will hold a Miami news
conference Wednesday to name specific actions they will take in the
next phase of their strike.
   ``Once union leaders realize that everybody can become involved
in a campaign's strategy and tactics, then they can win,'' he said.
   Rogers, who has incurred the wrath of some union leaders for his
maverick style, said his organization, Corporate Campaign Inc., is
working without a fee to help beat Frank Lorenzo, chairman of
Eastern parent Texas Air Corp. and a man considered one of union's
most formidable foes.
   ``This guy is a tough nut to crack,'' Rogers said of the man who
has come out on top in past union struggles with Continental
Airlines, another unit of Texas Air Corp. ``I think we can play an
important role in making this a successful struggle.''
   Rogers said he will contact 65,000 to 90,000 community and union
leaders nationwide and push for their support not only against
Eastern, but also against corporations that are investing in the
carrier.
   Rogers refused to name any specific actions he'd take against
Eastern investors.
   In past strikes, Rogers has caused controversy by forging ahead
in spite of the reservations of union leaders.
   ``Ray has a tremendous talent as an organizer, particularly in a
strike situation, to get members involved and enthusiastic,'' said
Alan Zack, spokesman for the United Food and Commercial Workers
union. ``Where he has a problem is that he sometimes tends to
substitute his judgment for that of the elected leadership.''
   The flight attendants union hired Rogers because they have faith
in his leadership abilities, said Judith A. Coughlin, the union's
financial secretary.
   ``We've had thousands of people ask us, `What can we do?''' she
said. ``We weren't able to give them the kinds of jobs which we
would like to have given them. Now we can.''
   ``We hired Ray Rogers the organizer, not Ray Rogers the
renegade,'' she said.

</TEXT>
