<FIRST>r f AM-Eastern-Immigration     07-09 0357</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eastern-Immigration,0374</SECOND>
<HEAD>INS Says Airline Allows Illegal Aliens To Enter Country</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Strikebound and financially troubled Eastern
Airlines may face a new problem _ with immigration officials who say
the carrier is doing little to stop illegal aliens from flying into
this country.
   Perry Rivkind, district director of the U.S. Immigration and
Naturalization Service, said Eastern has been warned repeatedly to
tighten up checks of aliens taking flights to the United States.
Rivkind said of particular concern has been an increase in Cuban
nationals arriving at Miami International Airport on Eastern flights
from Panama and other Latin countries.
   Forty-seven Cubans were arrrested Saturday for immigration
violations, he said.
   Rivkind said he plans to meet Monday with a federal prosecutor to
discuss possible charges against Eastern and Air Panama. Air Panama
may be linked to a phony passport operation, Rivkind said.
   ``The airlines have got to become much more responsible in that
area,'' Rivkind said Saturday. ``Eastern is very slack on this and
always has been.''
   Eastern spokesman James Ashlock denied the airline was lax in
checking documents. But he said there has been a problem with forged
papers.
   Airlines must check immigration papers before issuing a ticket to
a foreign national to come to the United States.
   ``We do admit, and I think we've explained this to INS, we're
coping with a flood of forged documents, no question about it. It's
an age-old problem in our business,'' Ashlock said.
   ``We will certainly study whatever complaint he plans to bring
up,'' Ashlock added.
   Some Cubans arrested last week told the INS they bought passports
in Panama, used them to board their flight, then gave the passports
to a Panamanian official before takeoff.
   ``Apparently in Panama, it appears that the Panamanian government
is condoning and actually arranging for Cubans to get on flights,''
Rivkind said. ``Possibly both Eastern Airlines and Air Panama staff
may have full knowledge of this.''
   Ashlock said he had heard nothing about passports collected on an
Eastern plane.
   ``I'm going to vigorously pursue this with the attorney
general,'' Rivkind said, saying Eastern's flight crew would had to
have known about the activity.
</TEXT>
