<FIRST>r f BC-UALStock     07-09 0248</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-UAL Stock,0258</SECOND>
<HEAD>UAL Stock Soars On Takeover Talk</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   UAL Corp., the parent of United Airlines, again
may be a takeover target, and trading in its shares closed out the
week with plenty of loft.
   UAL was the most active issue traded Friday on the New York Stock
Exchange, soaring by $13.50 a share to close at a new high of $166.
   Nearly 1.9 million shares changed hands Friday and the $166
eclipsed the previous 52-week high of $152.50 set the previous day.
   In a court ruling released Friday, U.S. District Judge James B.
Zagel of Chicago sided with the Air Line Pilots Association by
invalidating parts of a UAL contract with the Machinists union.
These provisions gave the Machinists the right to reopen their
contract and strike if the airline were acquired.
   United pilots argued that the provisions amounted to illegal
anti-takeover measures aimed at blocking the $110-per-share bid for
the company they first proposed in 1987.
   ``We have never abandoned our pursuit of the company,'' said Rick
Dubinsky, head of the United pilots unit. ``Those covenants were
impediments to our financing, and now they're apparently out of the
way.''
   Dubinsky said the union is considering a revised bid for the
airline.
   Even before news of the court ruling reached the market, there
was a buying surge earlier Friday, attributed by analysts to
speculation that an offer for UAL might come from its management.
   A UAL spokesman declined to comment on the developments.
